<h1>Dropdowns</h1>
<p>
	Dropdowns allow users to select from a list and should be clearly labeled to communicate the content inside it.
	Content inside dropdowns should be grouped by relativity and ranked on importance and/or value to a user.
</p>

<section>
	<h2 id="dropdowns-composition">Dropdown composition</h2>
	<p>Dropdown component consists of 3 elements:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>dropdown container (wraps dropdown toggle and dropdown content)</li>
		<li>dropdown toggle</li>
		<li>dropdown content</li>
	</ul>
	{{#component-demo codeOnly=true}}
		<div class="wds-dropdown">
			<div class="wds-dropdown__toggle">…</div>
			<div class="wds-dropdown__content">…</div>
		</div>
	{{/component-demo}}
</section>

<section>
	<h2 id="dropdowns-interactions">Interactions</h2>
	<p>
		On desktop, dropdown content is showing whenever user hovers over dropdown toggle. For touch
		devices when user taps on a dropdown toggle you need to add
		<code class="format-code">.wds-is-active</code> class to the parent
		<code class="format-code">.wds-dropdown</code> element.
		There should be only one dropdown open at any time, so you should also remove
		this class from all the other dropdowns.
	</p>
</section>

<section>
	<h2 id="dropdowns-arrow-position">Arrow vertical position</h2>
	<p>
		Dropdown arrow will be correctly positioned vertically if you use
		the following elements as the toggle:
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li><code class="format-code">.wds-button</code></li>
		<li><code class="format-code">.wds-tabs__tab</code></li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		However, if you wish to use other elements as dropdown toggle,
		you need to add custom <code class="format-code">padding-bottom</code> parameter
		to push the arrow down. In the examples below, we use text with chevron as toggle
		and add this padding locally.
	</p>
</section>

